The paper deals with computing Nash equilibria in sequential games with incomplete information, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The algorithm presented is based on primal-dual methods, which are commonly used in optimization and machine learning (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the numerical stability of the algorithm, which is a topic of interest in numerical analysis and scientific computing (cs.NA). The algorithm involves basic iterations and matrix operations, which are topics in linear algebra and numerical methods (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the sequence-form representation of games, which is a technique used in algorithmic game theory and computational social choice (cs.SI).
